BRUSSELS, Sept 28 (Reuters) - The European Union took a standoff with Italy on Friday after Italy flouted its demands for a massive budget deficit plan, but the bloc may take a more aggressive stance if it sticks to too bold a target.
Italy's Euroskeptic government is aiming for a budget deficit of 2.4% of gross domestic product (GDP) for the next three years, suggesting that there is still no debt reduction in the face of deficit reduction demands.
"We have no interest in the crisis between the Commission and Italy," the European Commission's Economic Affairs Commissioner for Economic Affairs said on Friday, "and he responded cautiously as the EU's recommendations and sanctions may have little impact on Italy.
EU officials and diplomats still hope that market forces will be able to persuade Italy to adjust its budget before it is formally presented to the European Commission in mid-October.
After the government announced its plans, the euro fell to its lowest level in nearly two weeks on Friday, while Italian bond yields hit their highest in three weeks.
If the deficit target remains unchanged by the October deadline, the European Commission could veto Italy’s draft budget, something the commission has never done to any country.
European Commission Vice President Dombrovskis later said at a meeting in the Latvian capital Riga on Friday that Italy's current fiscal plan "seems inconsistent with the Stability and Growth Pact," referring to the EU's fiscal rules.
But he did not say how that would trigger a reaction from the EU.
