Nearly 1,000 state-owned scenic spots cut ticket prices by more than half by more than 20%
[Abstract] As of September 28, all localities have issued or issued documents to the public announced 981 free opening or price reduction measures (free opening 74, 907 price reduction), Yunnan Shilin, Dali Santa, Yulong Snow Mountain, Guangxi Guilin Lijiang, Fujian Wuyi Mountain, Hunan Zhangjiajie, Shaanxi tamales, Jiangxi Sanqingshan, Xinjiang Kanas and other scenic spots have been implemented.
In order to implement the decision-making and deployment of the Central Economic Work Conference and the "Government Work Report", the National Development and Reform Commission issued the "Guiding Opinions on Improving the Ticket Price Formation Mechanism of State-owned Scenic Spots to Reduce Ticket Prices in Key State-owned Scenic Spots" (hereinafter referred to as the "Guiding Opinions") on June 28, requiring the improvement of the ticket price formation mechanism of state-owned scenic spots from the aspects of rationally defining the cost composition of ticket pricing, innovative price management methods, and strict implementation of pricing procedures, so as to ensure that the price of high-level state-owned scenic spots will be reduced by the end of September.
All localities have actively carried out their work in accordance with the deployment requirements, and have successively reduced the ticket prices of a number of key state-owned scenic spots.
As of September 28, the implementation or issuance of 981 scenic spots free or price reduction measures (free 74, 907 price reduction), of which 5A-level scenic spots 159, 4A scenic spots 534, a total of 693, accounting for 70.6%.
Of the 907 scenic spots that have reduced the price, 491 have dropped by more than 20%, accounting for 54.3%, and 214 have dropped by more than 30%, accounting for 23.6%.
Yunnan, Shandong, Guangxi, Shaanxi and other provinces have a large number of price reduction scenic spots, of which the number of price reduction scenic spots in Yunnan is more than 100, the overall decline of more than 30%.
Anhui, Chongqing and other 8 provinces (autonomous regions, municipalities) government pricing 5A level scenic spots all to achieve price cuts.
Yunnan Stone Forest, Dali Santa, Yulong Snow Mountain, Guangxi Guilin Lijiang, Fujian Wuyi Mountain, Hunan Zhangjiajie, Shaanxi tart and horses, Jiangxi Sanqingshan, Xinjiang Kanas and other scenic spots have implemented price cuts.
The gradual return of ticket prices to key state-owned scenic spots is conducive to accelerating the transformation and upgrading of tourism from ticket economy to industrial economy, niche tourism to mass tourism and scenic tourism to global tourism, which is conducive to forming a virtuous cycle of optimizing the supply structure of tourism and the steady expansion of tourism consumption demand, and promoting the sustainable and healthy development of scenic spots and tourism tourism.
At the same time, the National Development and Reform Commission stressed that all localities should strengthen the price order of scenic spots, guide scenic spots to improve services, and ensure that price cuts do not decrease.
In addition, the National Development and Reform Commission has carried out special inspections on issues such as the decline in ticket prices in individual scenic spots reflected by the recent media, requiring all localities to deal with them seriously, respond to social concerns in a timely manner, and effectively implement the price reduction in place.
The CCPIT carries out short-, medium- and long-term optimization work in an orderly manner
The Macao Trade and Investment Promotion Bureau has submitted a short-, medium- and long-term optimization work report on "major investment immigration" and "skilled immigration", and in addition to stepping up and implementing the various tasks in the report, it has also been continuously listening to the opinions of the society and continuously optimizing the contents of the report and related work.
The CCPIT will introduce the relevant optimization work to all sectors of society as soon as possible.
Of these, five are short-term measures to be implemented within this year; five are medium-term measures to be implemented in 2019; and one is long-term measures.
In addition, the CCPIT also comprehensively reviewed the internal management system in accordance with the instructions of the Secretary for Economic and Financial Affairs Leung Vitt.
The five short-term measures implemented this year include:
Carry out follow-up work. Priority is given to the investigation of cases that are about to expire in seven years, the cases mentioned in the CCAC report, and new renewal cases. If cases of misconduct or signs of illegality are found, they will voluntarily refer them to the relevant judicial authorities for follow-up;
On-site inspections involving "major investment immigration" projects. By the end of September, more than 20 investment projects had been inspected;
A comprehensive review of the current review system has been carried out. In reviewing the application for "major investment immigration", six principles for analyzing investment projects have been re-established; in the evaluation of "skilled immigration" applications, the relevant approval mechanism will be improved by clarifying the elements conducive to the development of Macao and the conditions for the preferential absorption of talents. At the same time, the annual list of "five industry ten jobs" for the introduction of talents has been established to meet the policy direction of the HKSAR Government and attract talents in a more targeted manner;
Increase transparency of information, including plans to gradually publish approval standards, scoring standards and proportions from the fourth quarter of this year, and further refine and make public approval data;
In terms of improving the work of the confirmation mechanism, it has been required to confirm the previous work in Australia; major investments must be verified on-site and financial statements submitted.
The five medium-term measures to be implemented in 2019 include:
Establish a mechanism to listen regularly to the views of the Committee on Talent Development and the Economic Development Committee. It has held a working meeting with the Economic Development Committee in September to discuss the establishment of relevant mechanisms.
Require applicants to submit financial statements made annually by independent third parties to review the operation of investment projects on an ongoing basis;
Further standardize and electronic the process of case application and approval to reduce human error;
Fully review the current staffing and cooperate with the implementation of a number of optimization measures;
Strengthen the study of the revision of the temporary residence system for investors, managers and specially qualified technicians.
