According to the trade agreement announced on Monday, the new U.S.-Mexico-Canada trade agreement will preserve the ability of U.S. President Donald Trump to implement the threat of a 25 percent tariff on imported cars, while essentially exempting imports of passenger cars, pickups and auto parts from Canada and Mexico from tariffs.
If Trump imposes so-called “Chapter 232” tariffs on cars for national security reasons, Mexico and Canada will have a quota for exempting 2.6 million cars from paying taxes to the United States each year.
Under the subsidiary arrangement, pickup trucks produced in both countries will be fully exempted from tariffs.
If Trump imposes auto tariffs, Mexico will get an annual auto parts exemption tax quota of $108 billion, and Canada will get a $32.4 billion quota.
Both quotas are much higher than the current production levels of the two countries, providing room for growth in their exports.
WASHINGTON/MEXICO (Reuters) - After days of debate, U.S. President Donald Trump’s administration and Canada are making concrete efforts to resolve trade policy differences, Mexico said on Friday, raising hopes that the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) will remain in the form of a three-way agreement.
Although there is a lack of detail, the obvious progress is enough to prompt the Mexican and US governments to suddenly stop publishing the text of the two-party trade agreement and give Canada more time to join the agreement.
Mexican President-elect Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador told reporters in Mexico that the U.S. government had made new counter-recommendations to the Canadian government and said he would continue to push all three countries to participate in NAFTA.
Mexican Economy Minister Ildefonso Guajardo said the time frame for submitting the text of the trade agreement between the two sides to Mexico and the United States was delayed because the Canadian and U.S. governments were “very serious” trying to reach an agreement.
"In the next 48 hours, we will know whether we have reached a text of the tripartite agreement or whether we have to publish the text of the two-party agreement," Guajardo said.
Guajardo said his U.S. and Canadian counterparts at the same level had "specially requested" to delay the release of the text.
A spokesman for the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative (USTR) did not comment on the text of the U.S.-Mexico trade agreement and the U.S.-Canada consultations.
Officials from the Office of the Prime Minister and the Office of the Foreign Minister did not respond to requests for comment on the counter-recommendations.
According to foreign media reports, in a conservation center on the outskirts of Pretoria, the capital of South Africa, two young lions play together, it is difficult to see any abnormalities, but they are unique.
The University of Pretoria announced: â€œThis is the first pair in the world to be born in artificial inseminationâ€ , the first in the world.â€
Scientists in the school are working on the reproductive system of the female lion.
Gans Winter, director of the Institute of Mammal Research at the University of Pretoria, said the two cubs, born on August 25, were healthy and normal.
After 18 months of intensive testing, his team finally reached this breakthrough.
“We take sperm from a healthy lion,” Gans Winter said in an interview with the media.
Next, the researchers and other lionesses have artificial insemination when the hormone content in the body is suitable.
Gans Winter said: "Fortunately, the result was successful."
He said the researchers "tried several attempts, but unexpectedly, they didn't take much effort."
He said the breakthrough could be repeated, and scientists hope to use the technology to save endangered big cats.
According to the International Union for Conservation of Nature, lions have become extinct in 26 African countries, and the total number of surviving wild lions has dropped by 43% in the past 20 years, leaving only about 20,000.
African lions are classified as vulnerable animals by this group.
Gans Winter said, "If we don't do something for these animals, they're going to be extinct."
He said the new technique doesn’t have to be kept in lions, but rather to inject sperm into fertile lionesses, just as they do with captive elephants in North America and Europe.
South Korea's exports fell in September by the most in more than two years, but analysts blamed fewer working days for the decline, saying global demand for South Korean goods remained strong despite rising U.S.-China trade tensions.
Indeed, South Korea’s daily exports increased last month.
In addition, preliminary data released earlier showed double-digit growth in exports in the first few weeks of September before the long holiday.
South Korea's exports fell in September from the largest year-on-year since July 2016, and the decline was larger than the 5.7 percent drop in the forecast of 11 analysts polled by Reuters.
Preliminary values released on Monday showed exports of $5.6 billion in September, down from $51.2 billion in August.
South Korea's exports to China rose 7.8 percent in September, expanding for the 23rd straight month, despite concerns that the growing U.S.-China trade dispute could hurt other Chinese neighbors, which is also hurting other Chinese neighbors.
South Korean exports to the United States fell 11.8 percent as sales of petroleum products fell.
Overseas sales of South Korean memory chips and petroleum products increased by 28.3% and 13.5%, respectively, although the market is worried that the so-called chip "super cycle" may have peaked.
“However, the impact of the trade conflict will be inevitable, as South Korea’s exports are heavily dependent on the U.S. and Chinese markets.”
Imports fell 2.1 percent to $40.4 billion, or 3.1 percent growth as forecast in a Reuters poll.
The initial trade surplus in September was $9.7 billion, up from $6.9 billion in August.
The Ministry of Industry said that thanks to the United States and EU countries, the global manufacturing industry will remain prosperous, which is a favorable factor for South Korean exports.
"The increase in export prices caused by the rise in oil prices will also be beneficial to exports in the second half of this year," the statement said.
"However, the continuation of the trade conflict between the United States and China, coupled with the increase in market volatility after the United States raised interest rates, are negative pressure on exports."
Exports on average on business days rose to $2.6 billion in September, compared to $2.1 billion in August.
South Korea's Mid-Autumn Festival falls from September 24-26 this year, so there are only 19.5 working days in September, four days less than the same period last year.
South Korea's exports in January-September increased by 4.7% compared with the same period last year.
According to the Nikkei/Markit Purchasing Managers’ Index, South Korea’s manufacturing activity picked up in September, but was supported by domestic orders as orders from China and Japan fell, which could cloud the prospect of another export.
