EU to reach crude oil purchase agreement with Iran
The U.S. government recently announced that it will restart a new round of sanctions on Iran in November, and even urged other countries to reduce imports of Iranian oil.
But America’s allies don’t seem to be listening.
According to the New York Times, on the 29th, Iranian Foreign Minister Zarif revealed in an interview that despite the threat of the United States to impose sanctions on any country doing business with Iran, Tehran is approaching an agreement with the European Union on the sale of crude oil.
The core purpose of the agreement is to try to establish a new payment mechanism, that is, to replace the US dollar transactions in barter or local currency.
The aim of the approach is to bypass the United States and prevent the United States from blocking financial transfers.
At the same time, while the EU is working on brokering the deal, some French and British officials are also concerned that if the agreement is realized, it will be the most open confrontation between the EU and the United States, which opposes the withdrawal of the United States from the Iran nuclear agreement.
In an hour-long interview, Zarif’s words sounded more optimistic than in recent months.
Because the agreement has the ability to "strip" the traditional allies of the United States and effectively break the US's attempts to reduce Iran's revenue.
"This ensures that we sell and benefit from oil," Zarif said, under the 2015 agreement, countries have the legal right to trade with Iran.
EU foreign policy chief Federica Mogherini recently said, "No sovereign state or organization can accept others to decide who they can trade with."
But she also predicted that before the U.S. government steps next sanctions in November, U.S. leaders may adopt a series of financial measures aimed at targeting banks, businessmen and countries that do business with Tehran.
In May, the U.S. government unilaterally withdrew from the Iran nuclear deal on the grounds that the agreement was flawed, saying it could not permanently ban Iran from producing nuclear fuel.
The U.S. then threatened to ban companies that buy Iranian oil and other goods from doing business in the United States.
The threat caused some companies to leave Tehran and Iran’s currency plummet.
Companies such as Airbus and French oil giant Total have cancelled billions of dollars in investment in Iran.
British and French officials have said the U.S. government could "have the upper hand."
Of course, according to a recent report by the Turkish media, the US sanctions do not seem to have a great impact on Iran's oil exports.
Iran's oil minister recently revealed that no other country except South Korea has stopped buying Iranian oil.
Both Zarif and Iranian President Hassan Rouhani believe that the purpose of a series of US actions is to "tempt" Iran to violate the agreement.
Zarif was also dismissive of a series of verbal attacks by the U.S. side, and when asked whether the United States would topple the current Iranian government with increasing fiscal pressure, Zarif even laughed, "It is a regime change strategy, which is the real purpose of the United States."
