Under a settlement, U.S.-based Tesla Motors and its chief executive, Musk, have agreed to pay $20 million in fines to financial regulators, and Musk will step down as chairman of the company but remain CEO.
The settlement will bring an end to two months of turmoil for Tesla.
The settlement of the securities fraud allegations disclosed by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission on Saturday will give investors a breath.
Investors had feared a protracted legal battle would only further blow the losing-lose electric car company.
The SEC sued Musk on Thursday for fraud, saying its August 7 tweet misled investors.
The tweet said he was considering taking Tesla private at $420 a share and had secured financing.
The SEC said the tweets were virtually unfounded and that the market turmoil they triggered hurt investors.
Investors and corporate governance experts say the deal could strengthen Tesla, which has been hit hard by Musk’s recent actions.
Steven Heim, head of Boston Common Asset Management, said the settlement should put Musk under more oversight and did not take “devastating” measures to drive him out of Tesla.
The asset management firm holds shares in Tesla’s battery maker Panasonic.
Under the proposed agreement, Tesla must appoint an independent chairman, two independent directors, and a board committee to develop controls on Musk’s external communications.
"It is in the best interests of our market and our investors, including Tesla shareholders, to resolve this matter quickly and on agreed terms," SEC Chairman Clayton said in a statement.
Thursday's allegations caused Tesla's market value to evaporate about $7 billion, and the company's market value was $45.4 billion on Friday, down from GM's $47.5 billion.
In the settlement agreement, the SEC withdrew the request to remove Musk from the head of the company.
Many investors said the penalty would be catastrophic.
"I think this is the best possible outcome for everyone involved," said Ivan Feinseth of Tigress Financial Partners, who gave Tesla a "null" rating and called the SEC's penalty a "light penalty" for Musk.
"He's still CEO is important to Tesla."
Neither Musk nor Tesla acknowledged or denied the SEC’s allegations in the settlement, nor did they immediately respond to a request for comment.
The settlement agreement still needs to be approved by the court.
