Korean chicken soup exports to China surge 20-fold in 4 years or related to the increase of empty nest youth
Korean chicken soup exports to China surged 20 times in four years Analysis: related to the increase of empty nest youth
Yonhap News Agency reported on the 5th that the export value of Korean chicken soup to China last year exceeded 100,000 US dollars, a sharp increase of about 20 times compared with 2013 four years ago.
According to the analysis, this increase is related to the increase in the number of empty nesters in China, which drives the popularity of convenience food sales, and the attention of young people to nutritious meals.
The data was released by the Korea Agricultural and Aquatic Food Circulation Corporation (aT) on the 5th.
Last year, South Korea's chicken soup exports to China amounted to 10.0339 million U.S. dollars, weighing 21.859 million kilograms, a sharp increase of 2094% and 3668.8% respectively in 2013.
According to the analysis, the increase in sales of Korean chicken soup in China is related to the increase in the number of empty nest youth driving the hot sales of convenience food, and the attention of young people to nutritious meals.
As of this year, China's one-person households have exceeded the 200 million mark, and it is expected to increase to 30% of the total population in 2020, and local food companies have also launched a variety of convenience foods aimed at the "single rice family".
In addition, the analysis also said that avian influenza is the biggest factor hindering chicken soup from taking root in the mainland Chinese market.
aT said that from November 2016 to April last year, there was a bird flu epidemic in South Korea, and the relevant departments completely banned the export of chicken soup to China, resulting in a sharp reduction in export value.
In 2016, chicken soup exports to China amounted to 840,000 US dollars, and due to avian influenza, exports plummeted to $100,000 last year.
