During the 73rd session of the United Nations General Assembly, various parties released some positive information on the Korean Peninsula issue.
South Korean President Moon Jae-in relayed North Korea's "irreversible" determination to denuclearize and said U.S. President Donald Trump and North Korea's top leader, Kim Jong Un, could meet before the end of the year.
The U.S. State Department later said Secretary of State Mike Pompeo would visit North Korea in October to advance the implementation of the U.S.-North Korea leaders' Singapore meeting commitments.
Since the beginning of this year, the DPRK and the ROK have broken the ice and opened the road of dialogue, the leaders of the DPRK and the ROK and the DPRK and the United States have held meetings, and the general trend of easing the situation on the Korean Peninsula has continued, and the principle of resolving the Korean Peninsula issue has been adhered to.
First of all, the fact that the "mainty of the Korean Peninsula issue is security issues" has not changed. The key to achieving peace on the Peninsula is to properly and balance the reasonable security concerns of all parties, rather than blindly exerting pressure on the other side and emphasizing their own demands.
Second, in the dialogue on the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula, the parties concerned are still divided on the steps and methods of realizing the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula. Due to the long-term lack of political trust between the DPRK and the US, the game thinking of "who comes first and then" is still strong.
At the Security Council Open Meeting on the Korean Peninsula issue held at the United Nations Headquarters in New York a few days ago, the different voices of all parties on the issue of sanctions against the DPRK once again highlighted that these two points on the Korean Peninsula issue have not changed.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo insisted that sanctions on North Korea would not be lifted until the Korean peninsula was fully denuclearized.
Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov stressed the principle of "responding to action by action", noting that "the trend of weakening sanctions should be the same steps as North Korea's steps on the path of gradual denuclearisation."
There is no doubt that the parties concerned should continue to implement the DPRK-related resolutions of the Security Council in a comprehensive, complete and accurate manner, but pressure is not the goal, and the implementation of sanctions and the promotion of political solutions are the requirements of the Security Council resolutions.
As Chinese State Councilor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi said, in view of the current positive developments in inter-Korean and DPRK-US relations, China believes that it is necessary for the Security Council to consider the timely initiation of reversible clauses to encourage the DPRK and relevant parties to take greater steps towards denuclearization.
Looking back, every progress in the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula and the peace process requires sufficient political courage on all sides.
At present, in the face of the growing expectations of the international community to promote the political settlement of the Korean Peninsula issue, the relevant parties should especially show political strength and make political decisions, implement commitments and resolve difficult problems, continue to take steps to meet each other, advance the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula and establish a peace mechanism on the Peninsula in parallel, and jointly create a permanent peace on the Peninsula.
