TOKYO, Oct 1 (Reuters) - Confidence among Japan’s biggest manufacturers hit their lowest level in more than a year in September, according to the Bank of Japan’s quarterly report on Monday, as rising raw material costs and a series of natural disasters have weighed on companies.
The survey did little show that escalating global trade frictions have dampened the confidence of large manufacturers.
But the risk of a full-blown trade war has hit companies’ business prospects and could threaten their capital spending.
Active capital spending is a bright spot in the Japanese economy.
The survey calls into question the Bank of Japan’s view that a robust economic expansion will help accelerate inflation toward its 2 percent target, despite signs that companies are gradually passing on costs to customers.
"In the face of concerns caused by the global trade war, the confidence of manufacturers has stagnated due to the slowdown in exports and weak factory production," said Nan Wuzhi, chief researcher at the Institute of Agriculture and Forestry.
"Fun confidence is still high. And because corporate earnings are improving and prices are rising, I don't think confidence will continue to decline."
The short-term survey showed that the large-scale manufacturing business sentiment judgment index fell to 19 in September from positive 21 three months ago, worsening for the third consecutive quarter.
The median market estimate is positive 22.
The large non-manufacturing sentiment judgment index fell to positive 22 in September from 24 in the June survey, the first deterioration in eight quarters.
Reuters polled at 22.
According to the survey, the large-scale manufacturing and non-manufacturing economic judgment indexes are expected to remain stable in December.
Investors were unconcerned about the decline in the short-term business sentiment index, with the Nikkei .N225 rising to a 27-year high on Monday as the yen’s continued depreciation helped improve the export earnings outlook for Japanese companies.
Capital expenditures are robust.
While business confidence has declined, the latest short-term outlook highlights the robustness of corporate capital spending plans, helped by increased capacity and increased investment in robotics and automation in response to an aging population.
According to the central bank's short-term survey, large enterprises plan to increase capital expenditures by 13.4% in the fiscal year ending March 2019.
The previous short-term survey was 13.6%.
Nan said that all corporate capital expenditure plans for the fiscal year will grow by 8.5%, close to the pace of Japan's bubble economy.
“Given that small businesses are raising their profit forecasts from now on, there is still room for further growth in capital spending, but that depends largely on the impact of the trade war on business confidence,” he said.
The increased ability of companies to pass on costs and a positive seven-year high in the output price index of large companies is a decade-old high, a sign that reflects progress in Japan’s efforts to combat deflation.
The index, which measures employment in large enterprises, hit minus 23, the most tight level since 1992, highlighting the tightening of the job market.
Thanks to strong corporate spending, Japan’s economy rebounded in the second quarter from its contraction in January-March.
But the escalating trade frictions in the summer and the disruption of the supply chain due to natural disasters have clouded the economic outlook for export-dependent Japan.
