69th International Astronautical Congress opens in Germany
Xinhua News Agency, Bremen, Germany, October 1 (Reporter Ren Ke Zhang Yirong) The 69th International Astronautical Congress kicked off on October 1 at the Bremen Convention and Exhibition Center in Germany, attended by more than 6,300 astronauts, space agencies and business representatives, experts, scholars and young students from all over the world.
Jean-Yves Legal, President of the International Astronautical Federation, said in his speech at the opening ceremony that the global space industry is no longer the participation of only a few countries and institutions, and the number of participants this year has increased significantly compared with the previous one, indicating that more and more institutions and people are joining it.
He called on all countries to strengthen cooperation and innovation and jointly promote the development of the space industry.
Zhang Kejun, Vice Minister of Industry and Information Technology of China and Director of the State Space Administration, introduced China's space program when he attended the exchange event and said that China will expand international cooperation in the space field and contribute to the human space industry.
Representatives of relevant institutions such as China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation and China Aerospace Science and Industry Corporation, as well as some private enterprises, participated in the meeting, showing the latest achievements of China's aerospace industry, including various types of launch vehicles, satellites and aerospace science and technology applications.
The International Astronautical Congress has been held annually since 1950 and is the largest event in the world aviation community.
The five-day conference was co-sponsored by the International Astronautical Federation, the International Academy of Astronautics, the Center for Applied Science and Microgravity Research at the University of Bremen and the International Society of Space Law.
