More than 90 percent of Brazilian voters say presidential candidates are not considering women’s needs.
According to data released by Brazil's National Geographic Institute (IBGE), more than 90% of Brazilian women do not think that presidential candidates consider women's needs.
At present, the number of women in Brazil has reached 107 million, and if women from all of Brazil are gathered to form a country, the country's population will be ranked 13th in the world, more than twice the population of Spain.
In Brazil, women account for 52% of the total electorate and 48% of men. Although the proportion of women in the electorate is very high, only 10% of the Brazilian Congress is female.
Of the 193 countries in the world, Brazilian women are only 154th in politics, higher than in Arab countries.
After more than 20 years of rights struggle, Brazilian women have not succeeded in gaining their rights.
Natalia Mori, a Brazilian sociologist, points out that this phenomenon is the result of ancient patriarchal society, racism, and the combination of capitalist values.
"Politics should be the people who advocate for civil rights, identity, access to public goods and the same society by multiple social groups. But Brazilian politics is a monopoly of a certain group, and the majority of the population is not represented."
A previous study by Locomotiva also pointed out that 94% of Brazilian women do not feel that the elected politicians can represent their rights, 90% of Brazilian women do not agree with the decisions made by politicians, and 93% of women do not agree with the current government's governance policies.
"We need to reverse the underrepresentation of women in parliament, where the political system is still affected by inequality. So far, there are still serious gender, class and racial discrimination in Brazil's political sphere," said Natalia Morrie.
Despite women’s rights, most Brazilian women still believe in the power of democracy.
The survey showed that 76 per cent of women believed they could make a difference in democratic elections and 72 per cent were interested in politics.
In addition, 55% of women believe that democracy is the best way to expose women to less prejudice.
