Systemic lupus erythematosus is a chronic and difficult disease that involves multiple organs throughout the body and has been considered an "incurable disease" in the past.
Because of its unclear pathogenesis, diagnosis and treatment are difficult, and there is a lack of effective treatment.
Recently, Liu Wanli, a researcher at the School of Life Sciences of Tsinghua University, and the joint team of Li Zhanguo, director of the Rheumatological Immunity Center of Peking University People's Hospital, discovered that human immunoglobulin has molecular variation that increases the susceptibility of systemic lupus erythematosus, and this variation is involved in regulating immune B cells.
In short, the two teams confirmed that an abnormal immune molecule in the human body is an important cause of the systematic onset of lupus erythematosus.
According to one of the authors of the article, Sun Xiaolin of Peking University People's Hospital, the team collected nearly 2,000 large samples of systemic lupus patients and conducted research, and found that patients with immunoglobulin variants produced disease-causing cells and a wide variety of autoantibodies, and the incidence and severity of inflammation such as nephritis, arthritis, plasma, and vasculitis increased significantly.
Through various research methods such as immune cell tracking, animal testing, sequencing, etc., Liu Wanli's team found that the immune signaling pathway activated by this immune molecular variant and the pathogenesis of B cells to secrete a variety of autoantibodies.
The reporter learned that the two teams are strong and united, giving full play to their respective advantages, and achieving a close integration of basic research and clinical applications.
Liu Wanli's team is committed to the study of immune recognition and immune activation of B lymphocytes, and the team of Li Zhanguo has long been engaged in clinical research on systemic lupus.
"This study is one of the results of years of cooperation between the two teams, and the first time in the academic community to recognize that immunoglobulin gene abnormalities will induce systemic lupus erythematosus, laying a solid foundation for further academic research and clinical targeted therapy."
