Since the mid-2000s, as China’s demand for oilseeds has grown, Paul Thomas, a North Dakota farmer, has grown more and more soybeans in his land.
The shift peaked this year, with him planting 1,600 acres of soybeans on 5,000 acres of land, a scale never seen before.
But Thomas and many farmers like him plan to switch to the staple crops of the former U.S. agricultural region in 2019: corn and wheat.
U.S. farmers planted more soybeans than corn this year for the first time in 35 years.
The reason for the plan to switch to other food crops is because in the context of US President Trump's trade war with China, American farmers are facing difficulties in selling soybeans.
China typically buys about 60 percent of U.S. soybeans, but because of the trade war, nearly zero purchases of U.S. soybeans in recent months have sent soybean prices to a decade-long low.
Thomas plans to plant more wheat next year, hoping to make more money by reducing dependence on crops that depend on Chinese demand.
Thomas said soybean prices "have hit us hard."
Without Chinese demand, he said, the spot price of soybeans near his farm was $7.10 per bushel, while the price necessary to cover the cost was $8.50.
U.S. farmers planted a record amount of soybeans this year, and the harvest is also expected to hit a record high.
At such a time when they are vulnerable, they have encountered the blow of the trade war.
In response to Trump's imposition of tariffs on imports of Chinese goods, China imposed import tariffs on imports of U.S. soybeans in July.
The U.S. Department of Agriculture will release its first estimate for next year’s planting area, which is expected to include considerations of the impact of the tariffs.
The forecast is expected to confirm the expectations of private institutions for a reduction in soybean planting area.
According to a report seen by Reuters, Informa Economics on October 19 expected corn planting to increase by 4% to 92.7 million acres (37.5 million hectares) in 2019, and soybean planting area to decrease by 7% to 83 million acres.
Informa also expects U.S. wheat acreage to increase by 4%.
Soybean grown before retaliatory tariffs rose to 89.6 million acres this year, about 15 million acres higher than a decade ago.
Corn cultivation has increased by less than 5 million acres since 2008 to 98.1 million acres, and this year’s wheat planting area is 41.8 million acres, near its lowest level in 100 years.
Aron Carlson, president of the Illinois Corn Growers Association, has a total 3,600-acre acre plant, and he’s spending nearly half on soybeans this year, but plans to cut back in the future.
He said it was possible to increase corn cultivation by up to 20 percent at his northern Illinois farm, the largest soybean-growing state in the United States.
Soybeans yield less per acre than corn, but also require less fertilizer, which makes soybeans generally less expensive to grow.
If farmers move to final corn, it may raise costs, but it will benefit some businesses, including Andersons Inc. fertilizer sellers.
Andersons chief executive Pat Bowe told Reuters he expected the conversion of corn would be beneficial for fertilizer use.
Bayer is also expected to benefit from the conversion of farmers to corn.
