BEIJING, Sept 30 (Reuters) - The People’s Bank of China on Sunday released data on short-term outflows of foreign currency assets, which showed that the central bank’s short positions on foreign currency forwards and futures contracts as of the end of August were zero for 12 consecutive months, with no long positions remaining in the month.
The central bank's previous data show that as of the end of August last year, the central bank held a total of foreign currency to local currency forward contracts and futures contracts short positions of 6.044 billion US dollars, unchanged for the fourth consecutive month; the short position in SDR (special draw rights) was 4.276 billion SDR.
Since then, the central bank’s foreign exchange forward short position has been zero.
The central bank first released the data at the end of March 2016; the data showed that the central bank's foreign currency foreign currency forward and futures contracts long positions at the end of February 2016 were US$2.438 billion, and the short position was $28.9 billion.
The September data released at the end of October of the same year showed a net increase of $16,401 million to $45,301 million.
The central bank has previously said that the foreign currency forward and futures short positions mainly reflect the central bank's foreign exchange forward operations with commercial banks to meet the hedging needs of corporate foreign currency liabilities, and will continue to provide forward-haven products in accordance with the principle of real demand, and the central bank's forward operation will have less impact on the scale of future foreign exchange reserves.
