In recent years, there have been unqualified incidents of campus plastic runways in many places.
To this end, the Ministry of Education issued a notice requiring the delivery of primary and secondary school composite materials after November 1 this year must implement the new national standard.
The mandatory national standard "Primary and secondary school synthetic material surface sports field" is led by the Ministry of Education, 26 scientific research institutes and testing institutions to participate in the drafting, after more than two years of revision, during which more than 100 expert meeting demonstrations have been organized, as well as nationwide field visits, sampling tests, collected hundreds of enterprises on the market products countless verification experiments.
Reporters compared with the 2005 old national standard found that the new national standard not only changed from the "national recommended standard" to the "national mandatory standard", but also added a lot of content, including thickness requirements, physical properties, weather resistance, inorganic filler content requirements, anti-slip rubber particles high-polymer content requirements, surface layer of finished harmful substances limited, non-solid and solid raw material harmful substances limited.
In particular, it is worth mentioning that the new national standard limits the harmful substances that may be generated in the construction of plastic runways on campus, from the original 7 items to 18 items, and the limits of volatile organic compounds on the completed runway are stipulated in accordance with the home improvement standards.
For example, the release of harmful substances in the "current and prefabricated surface products in the amount of harmful substances and odor requirements" is clearly stipulated, requiring that the total volatile organic compounds shall not be higher than 5 mg/m3, formaldehyde shall not be higher than 0.4 mg/m3, carbon disulfide shall not be higher than 7 mg/m3, benzene shall not be higher than 0.1 mg/m3, and the odor level shall not be higher than 3.
The new national standard also makes detailed provisions on the sampling requirements, inspection rules and judgment rules for plastic runways in primary and secondary schools.
In addition, the campus artificial turf is also included in the scope of mandatory testing of the national standard for the first time.
In the near future, all localities should carry out special work deployment on the implementation of the new national standard, and report the implementation of the new national standard to the Department of Sports Health and Arts Education of the Ministry of Education during the year.
